    "summary": "The Battle of the Bulge (December 16, 1944 – January 25, 1945) was the last major German offensive on the Western Front of [[event:112|World War II]]. Hitler ordered the offensive, codenamed Operation Watch on the Rhine, to split Allied lines through the Ardennes forest in Belgium and Luxembourg, capture the vital supply port of Antwerp, and potentially force a separate peace with the Western Allies. The attack initially achieved surprise, creating a large salient (bulge) in Allied lines.\n\nGerman forces advanced rapidly in the first days, capturing thousands of Allied prisoners, with the massacre of 84 American prisoners by SS troops at Malmedy becoming one of the war's most notorious war crimes. The critical road junction of Bastogne, defended by the 101st Airborne Division, held out against German encirclement. Brigadier General Anthony McAuliffe's single-word reply of 'Nuts' to a German surrender demand became famous. Clearing weather in late December allowed Allied air power to intervene, and the German advance was halted and then reversed.\n\nThe battle was the costliest in American history by casualties: approximately 75,000 American soldiers were killed, wounded, or captured. German losses were equally severe, and the offensive consumed irreplaceable fuel, armor, and experienced troops that Germany could not replace. The failure of the Ardennes offensive accelerated the Allied advance into Germany in the final months of the war.",
